habitat_description: Larus occidentalis nests in areas sheltered from the wind and free of terrestrial predators, such rock crevices on islands and isolated mainland cliffs (Grinnell and Miller, 1944; Pierotti and Annett, 1995). The species forages at sea and along sandy beaches, tidal mudflats, piers, and garbage dumps (Grinnell and Miller, 1944; Pierotti and Annett, 1995; Webb and Blumenstein, 2005). Western gulls roost in open areas such as parking lots and fields (Pierotti and Annett, 1995). The species can be found at least 50 miles out to sea (Sanger, 1973), and it rarely ventures inland (Grinnell and Miller, 1944).
